title: Kamala Harris returns to Australia because Americans ‘want to get rid of her’
description: Sky News host Rowan Dean reacts to former US vice president Kamala Harris returning to Australia.   “She keeps coming here to talk to us,” Mr Dean said.  “Maybe it's just Americans want to get rid of her for a few days.”

title: AOC blasted for not having the ‘confidence’ to be a world leader
description: Author and commentator Shemeka Michelle claims Democratic Representative Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez “isn’t the right fit” for the Democratic Party.   “I just don’t think she understands what is going on,” Ms Michelle told Sky News host Rowan Dean.  Ms Michelle also says she does not have the “confidence needed to be a world leader”.

title: ‘Fall from grace’: Anthony Albanese weighs in on Andrew Mountbatten-Windsor investigation
description: Sky News Political Editor Andrew Clennell interviews Prime Minister Anthony Albanese about his thoughts on the arrest of former prince Andrew Mountbatten-Windsor.

title: South Australian Liberal Party’s ‘lack of leadership’ analysed
description: Former Queensland premier Campbell Newman says the South Australian Liberal Party is facing a lack of leadership as a result of poor “policy differentiation”.   “That primary vote, I think of 14 per cent is a testament to a lack of leadership from the Liberal Party,” Mr Newman told Sky News host Steve Price.  “A lack of clear policy differentiation up against … a right-wing Labor premier.”

title: Sydney to Newcastle high-speed rail sparks debate over its use case
description: Former Queensland premier Campbell Newman details the cost of the Sydney to Newcastle high-speed rail.  “Why do we need a fast train between Sydney and Newcastle? Like, it would be great,” Mr Newman told Sky News host Steve Price.  “Surely, it’s Sydney-Melbourne.”

title: World’s Gone Mad: AI clip has Hollywood in an ‘absolute panic’
description: Sky News host Rowan Dean reacts to an artificial intelligence clip that has Hollywood in an “absolute panic”.

title: Pauline Hanson slams Peter Malinauskas’ One Nation comments
description: One Nation Leader Pauline Hanson slams South Australian Premier Peter Malinauskas’ comments about One Nation.  “What an absolute stupid comment to make with regard to One Nation,” Ms Hanson told Sky News host Steve Price.  “He needs to look at the hospital ramping, the educational system, what’s happening in South Australia … the cost-of-living.”

title: King Charles given ‘no heads up’ on ex-prince Andrew's arrest
description: The Daily Mirror Royal Editor Russell Myers says there was “no heads up” to the Royal Family that police were going to arrest former-prince Andrew at Sandringham residence, despite the investigation clearly gaining momentum.  “The public would have known this would have happened. Certainly, the investigation was gathering pace over the last few days,” Mr Myers told Sky News host Caleb Bond.  “The police will want to get it right; they want to be seen doing the right thing because the public sense of revulsion in this whole episode is quite high.”

title: Prince William wanted ex-prince Andrew exiled years before king stripped titles
description: The Daily Mirror Royal Editor Russell Myers claims Prince William had a “very staunch” view of former prince Andrew after the 2019 BBC Newsnight interview.  “He thought he should be exiled from the public and privately from the family,” Mr Myers told Sky News host Caleb Bond.  “Just look at that image of him leaving the police station last night … essentially hiding from public view under the cover of darkness.”

title: ‘Deeply embarrassed’: Royal Family rocked by Epstein scandal
description: The Daily Mirror Royal Editor Russell Myers believes the Royal Family is “deeply embarrassed” by shocking revelations in the Epstein Files.  “That is why you’ve seen the king making such an unprecedented statement saying the law must take its course,” Mr Myers told Sky News host Caleb Bond.  “It’s a complete stain on the monarchy, and no doubt we will see further statements.”

title: New book reveals behind-the-scenes Royal drama of Prince William and Princess Catherine
description: The Daily Mirror Royal Editor Russell Myers discusses his new book on Prince William and Princess Catherine.  “Certainly, we’ve heard from other sides of the family, whether it's Harry or Megan, or the details of the former prince Andrew’s involvement in several of the scandals,” Mr Myers told Sky News host Caleb Bond.  “I thought it was interesting to look at the behind-the-scenes view of what all those big instances have been for the prince and princess of Wales.”

title: Reaction from the UK of Andrew’s arrest has been ‘seismic’
description: Spiked Online Editor Tom Slater claims there is a “clear sense of historical weight” to Andrew Mountbatten-Windsor being arrested.   “It’s already been seismic that we’ve seen a member of the Royal Family arrested for the first time since the 1700s,” Mr Slater told Sky News host Caleb Bond.   “He was arrested yesterday by police officers who swear allegiance to the crown.”

title: Andrew sweating in a ‘police cell’ despite past sweat claims
description: Journalist and broadcaster Daisy McAndrew says Andrew Mountbatten-Windsor will be “sweating now,” following his arrest on Thursday.  “In that infamous interview he did with BBC Newsnight, prince Andrew said it couldn’t have been him in the nightclub with Virginia Giuffre because she said he was sweaty and he's incapable of sweat,” Ms McAndrew told Sky News host Steve Price.  “A lot of people are saying I bet you he was sweating yesterday in that police cell.”

title: UK justice acts as ex-prince Andrew faces arrest while US figures escape accountability
description: Journalist and broadcaster Daisy McAndrew says former Prince Andrew’s arrest shows British justice is working, while senior US figures escape accountability.  “Why is it that it looks like British justice is working, whereas American justice isn't?” Ms McAndrew told Sky News host Steve Price.  “No senior American politician or anyone else of note seems to have felt the long arm of the law.”

title: Calls for ‘two-year ban’ on immigration to boost Australia’s economy
description: Former speaker of the House Bronwyn Bishop calls for a “two-year ban” on immigrants coming to Australia.   “None, let's build the economy and give it some strength back,’ Ms Bronwyn Bishop told Sky News host Rowan Dean.  “But then you can have a policy that says we prefer to take people from a particular group who have got particular skills that we need.”
